sold her vase to an aid worker.

255
00:29:29,260 --> 00:29:32,427
The law also prevents
refugees from leaving the camp

256
00:29:32,429 --> 00:29:35,263
Unless they have
a jordanian sponsor.

257
00:29:35,265 --> 00:29:37,064
But in order
to make a living,

258
00:29:37,066 --> 00:29:39,433
Syrian refugees
overcome this barrier

259
00:29:39,435 --> 00:29:41,435
By partnering
with jordanians,

260
00:29:41,437 --> 00:29:44,171
Who bring supplies
in and out of the camp.

261
00:29:44,173 --> 00:29:47,440
Syrians are finding ways
to work and be productive

262
00:29:47,442 --> 00:29:49,809
By any means possible.

263
00:29:51,444 --> 00:29:55,113
Here you have 100,000 people
in front of you,

264
00:29:55,115 --> 00:29:56,481
And all that
they're begging for

265
00:29:56,483 --> 00:29:58,916
Is to be recognized
as human beings

266
00:29:58,918 --> 00:30:01,885
And not be just served
some assistance

267
00:30:01,887 --> 00:30:04,554
Which may not always be adapted
to what they want.

268
00:30:08,458 --> 00:30:10,459
people were showing us

269
00:30:10,461 --> 00:30:14,162
That they have a different
concept of the space,

270
00:30:14,164 --> 00:30:18,799
A different concept of how their
settlement should look like.

271
00:30:20,201 --> 00:30:22,569
We were building a camp.

272
00:30:22,571 --> 00:30:25,305
They were building a city.

273
00:30:25,307 --> 00:30:28,007
in just two years,
syrian refugees

274
00:30:28,009 --> 00:30:30,976
Have developed
a multi-million-dollar economy.

275
00:30:32,912 --> 00:30:35,413
At the center of the camp
is a thriving market street

276
00:30:35,415 --> 00:30:37,415
Jokingly named
the champs-elysées.

277
00:30:39,184 --> 00:30:40,817
We're riding
on a donkey

278
00:30:40,819 --> 00:30:42,451
Through the
champs-elysées.

279
00:30:44,087 --> 00:30:46,120
With over
3,000 business,

280
00:30:46,122 --> 00:30:48,589
You can buy
almost anything.

281
00:30:48,591 --> 00:30:50,891
The un  has never
seen a camp's economy

282
00:30:50,893 --> 00:30:53,293
Expand so quickly.

283
00:30:53,295 --> 00:30:55,862
Many camps forbid
this kind of growth.

284
00:30:55,864 --> 00:30:59,065
But syrians were determined
to rebuild their new lives.

285
00:30:59,067 --> 00:31:02,435
And the un has even
begun to embrace this vision,

286
00:31:02,437 --> 00:31:05,971
Putting za'atari
in a league all of its own.

287
00:31:08,407 --> 00:31:10,908
In addition to
this bustling economy,

288
00:31:10,910 --> 00:31:13,911
Our neighbors are
investing in their homes.

289
00:31:15,546 --> 00:31:17,847
They're moving
trailers to be near family

290
00:31:17,849 --> 00:31:19,481
And building
makeshift houses

291
00:31:19,483 --> 00:31:22,250
That have bedrooms, gardens,

292
00:31:22,252 --> 00:31:25,920
Private bathrooms,
and even fountains.

293
00:31:25,922 --> 00:31:29,223
This kind of growth
in za'atari is remarkable.

294
00:31:29,225 --> 00:31:32,459
But without the workings
of the city to support it,

295
00:31:32,461 --> 00:31:34,494
It can only go so far.

296
00:31:40,299 --> 00:31:43,067
In za'atari, there are
no household-level water

297
00:31:43,069 --> 00:31:45,235
And sewage systems.

298
00:31:45,237 --> 00:31:48,171
And the electrical grid
is completely overloaded.

299
00:31:50,374 --> 00:31:52,475
there are
limits to what we,

300
00:31:52,477 --> 00:31:55,544
As humanitarians,
can do.

301
00:31:55,546 --> 00:31:58,113
We are good
as humanitarians,

302
00:31:58,115 --> 00:32:00,315
As we are,
as the system is,

303
00:32:00,317 --> 00:32:02,350
To provide first aid.

304
00:32:02,352 --> 00:32:04,919
But we don't have
the capacity to work

305
00:32:04,921 --> 00:32:07,888
On medium- and
long-term strategies.

306
00:32:07,890 --> 00:32:11,324
We can pretend it,
but we don't have it.

307
00:32:11,326 --> 00:32:13,459
nonprofits and the un

308
00:32:13,461 --> 00:32:15,627
Don't have the
expertise to set up a city.

309
00:32:15,629 --> 00:32:19,430
They need support from city
planners and private companies

310
00:32:19,432 --> 00:32:21,331
To effectively run za'atari.

311
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:24,967
But the world hasn't stepped up

312
00:32:24,969 --> 00:32:28,437
To support jordanians,
the un  or syrians

313
00:32:28,439 --> 00:32:30,972
To pursue this kind of vision.

314
00:32:30,974 --> 00:32:34,308
Currently, za'atari
remains a short-term solution

315
00:32:34,310 --> 00:32:36,510
For a long-term problem.

316
00:33:06,073 --> 00:33:08,074
as we headed
into mafraq,

317
00:33:08,076 --> 00:33:09,675
It was almost
too much to think

318
00:33:09,677 --> 00:33:11,343
That za'atari
is only a fraction

319
00:33:11,345 --> 00:33:13,578
Of the refugees
in jordan.

320
00:33:13,580 --> 00:33:16,581
Most syrians
live outside of the camp.

321
00:33:16,583 --> 00:33:18,449
And one was our
neighbor ghoussoon.

322
00:33:20,585 --> 00:33:22,953
Like so many
of the families here,

323
00:33:22,955 --> 00:33:24,988
She's the head
of her household.

324
00:33:24,990 --> 00:33:27,223
One in four families
are led by a woman

325
00:33:27,225 --> 00:33:29,959
Because so many
men are still in syria.

326
00:33:29,961 --> 00:33:32,728
When did you make
that journey?

327
00:33:32,730 --> 00:33:36,398
Did you make it by yourself from
syria to mafraq?

328
00:34:04,025 --> 00:34:06,326
It's not easy. From
a gender perspective,

329
00:34:06,328 --> 00:34:09,595
Many women are expected
to stay inside the home.

330
00:34:09,597 --> 00:34:11,530
Of course, if you
have a female-headed
household,

331
00:34:11,532 --> 00:34:13,164
The woman doesn't
really have a choice.

332
00:34:13,166 --> 00:34:14,598
She has to leave
the home to find

333
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:16,733
Some kind of support
for her family,

334
00:34:16,735 --> 00:34:18,534
Financial
or otherwise.

335
00:35:30,439 --> 00:35:32,273
Wow.

336
00:35:33,809 --> 00:35:35,441
Incredible.

337
00:35:38,411 --> 00:35:40,378
even now,
when you have to provide

338
00:35:40,380 --> 00:35:42,146
For your whole family,

339
00:35:42,148 --> 00:35:43,680
Um, is there ever,
you know--

340
00:35:43,682 --> 00:35:45,548
Would you ever think
about going to za'atari,

341
00:35:45,550 --> 00:35:49,285
Where they give you free food
or they give you, uh...

342
00:35:49,287 --> 00:35:50,552
Different services?

343
00:35:53,355 --> 00:35:54,755
ghoussoon
arrived in jordan

344
00:35:54,757 --> 00:35:57,124
Before the refugee
camps were set up.

345
00:35:57,126 --> 00:35:59,626
She chooses not
to relocate to za'atari

346
00:35:59,628 --> 00:36:01,628
Because she believes
she can build

347
00:36:01,630 --> 00:36:04,631
A more traditional
home for her kids
outside of the camp,

348
00:36:04,633 --> 00:36:07,867
Where they can go
to public jordanian
schools.

349
00:36:44,503 --> 00:36:46,504
Hey!

350
00:36:55,612 --> 00:36:57,745
Who drew on this?
What is this?

351
00:37:01,449 --> 00:37:03,483
We have graffiti
on our--

352
00:37:03,485 --> 00:37:05,918
-Oh, yeah.
-I can't tell--
at least it's a heart.

353
00:37:08,455 --> 00:37:10,221
It says
"raouf's tent"?

354
00:37:10,223 --> 00:37:12,756
No, really?
Does it really?

355
00:37:15,626 --> 00:37:17,426
It says
"raouf's tent"?

356
00:37:18,628 --> 00:37:21,363
-Raouf?
-Abdel raouf.

357
00:37:21,365 --> 00:37:22,864
Did you do these?

358
00:37:27,602 --> 00:37:29,202
Thank you.

359
00:37:31,471 --> 00:37:33,738
My man raouf,
let's get inside.
It's cold.

360
00:37:33,740 --> 00:37:35,606
Yeah, it's cold.
Aren't you freezing?

361
00:37:43,180 --> 00:37:44,380
Did you clean--

362
00:37:47,584 --> 00:37:49,484
You cleaned the--

363
00:37:50,920 --> 00:37:53,287
Aw, raouf.

364
00:37:53,289 --> 00:37:54,921
Raouf, sit on
the mattress.

365
00:37:54,923 --> 00:37:56,422
I appreciate that.

366
00:37:57,390 --> 00:37:59,224
Dude, this kid
is the man.

367
00:37:59,226 --> 00:38:01,759
Did you go to school
in syria?

368
00:38:05,930 --> 00:38:07,596
What grade were you in
when you left?

369
00:38:11,367 --> 00:38:14,569
So, uh, what do you
want to be

370
00:38:14,571 --> 00:38:16,237
When you, uh, grow up?

371
00:38:18,340 --> 00:38:20,874
You want to be
a doctor? Nice.

372
00:38:20,876 --> 00:38:23,443
Have you always wanted
to be a doctor?

373
00:38:25,245 --> 00:38:27,813
He wants to help
the injured people.

374
00:38:27,815 --> 00:38:29,481
You want to help
the injured people?

375
00:38:31,751 --> 00:38:33,917
Like, the people
back in syria?

376
00:38:38,355 --> 00:38:41,557
There's a lot of school
before you can become
a doctor.

377
00:38:49,298 --> 00:38:50,965
And you're willing
to do it all?

378
00:38:54,935 --> 00:38:56,936
Yeah? Wow.

379
00:38:56,938 --> 00:38:59,638
Well, maybe--
can you be my doctor
when I'm--

380
00:38:59,640 --> 00:39:02,340
When you're a doctor?
I would love to
have a doctor.

381
00:39:09,981 --> 00:39:12,282
it's been
almost two years now,

382
00:39:12,284 --> 00:39:14,784
And raouf still doesn't
want to go to school.

383
00:39:14,786 --> 00:39:16,719
He says he doesn't
want to go

384
00:39:16,721 --> 00:39:19,088
Until he's back at
home in syria.

385
00:39:23,860 --> 00:39:26,895
We've been trying to
convince him to start
again,

386
00:39:26,897 --> 00:39:29,030
But the sad truth of it
is,

387
00:39:29,032 --> 00:39:32,400
Only half of refugee
kids are getting an education.

388
00:39:40,808 --> 00:39:44,143
What's up, raouf? Hey.

389
00:39:44,145 --> 00:39:45,444
Are you gonna
go today?

390
00:39:49,482 --> 00:39:52,050
-He doesn't know?
-He doesn't.

391
00:39:52,052 --> 00:39:53,584
You don't know?

392
00:39:53,586 --> 00:39:55,519
Well, you have--
what time is it?

393
00:39:55,521 --> 00:39:57,621
-It's almost 12:00.
-30 minutes.

394
00:39:57,623 --> 00:39:59,689
Why don't you want to go today?
Why don't you go?

395
00:40:04,594 --> 00:40:06,861
They'll help you
find your class, raouf.

396
00:40:06,863 --> 00:40:08,596
Right when you
walk in--

397
00:40:08,598 --> 00:40:10,965
And we can even walk
with you down there,
if you want,

398
00:40:10,967 --> 00:40:13,567
And then,
when you walk in,

399
00:40:13,569 --> 00:40:15,769
The organization
will help show you
where you class is,

400
00:40:15,771 --> 00:40:17,137
And you're
all registered,

401
00:40:17,139 --> 00:40:18,605
So you won't have
anything to worry about.

402
00:40:21,408 --> 00:40:22,608
No?

403
00:40:27,046 --> 00:40:29,881
Raouf, like, why don't
you want to go to school?

404
00:40:31,683 --> 00:40:33,550
Because you can
go to school
if you want to go.

405
00:40:41,157 --> 00:40:43,591
Why don't you
eat right now,
then let's go?

406
00:40:47,095 --> 00:40:49,529
I promise you,
you could be there
in ten minutes.

407
00:40:59,038 --> 00:41:00,872
Why don't we go?
We'll prove you wrong.

408
00:43:22,242 --> 00:43:24,676
I had no idea
that it was, like--

409
00:43:24,678 --> 00:43:26,577
It's trauma-based.

410
00:43:26,579 --> 00:43:28,879
Not, like, it's--
I mean--

411
00:43:28,881 --> 00:43:31,715
I think there's so many
factors involved now.

412
00:43:31,717 --> 00:43:33,817
But he's just scared.

413
00:43:33,819 --> 00:43:37,820
And, like, he has
a reason to be...

414
00:43:39,155 --> 00:43:41,623
Yeah, no ten-year-old
should ever have
to live with that.

415
00:43:46,761 --> 00:43:47,961
Jesus.

416
00:43:50,064 --> 00:43:51,998
You can have
some water, raouf.

417
00:43:56,370 --> 00:43:59,638
Your life
is way more complicated
than we thought it was.

418
00:44:01,073 --> 00:44:02,306
What's up, buddy?

419
00:44:02,308 --> 00:44:03,940
Did you beat zach
at soccer?

420
00:44:05,610 --> 00:44:07,142
You beat him up?

421
00:44:33,669 --> 00:44:36,070
Because it's, like,
a combination

422
00:44:36,072 --> 00:44:40,240
Of, like, a lot of
things that all come
together at one time.

423
00:44:48,983 --> 00:44:51,250
It's, like, always
just right under
the surface,

424
00:44:51,252 --> 00:44:53,051
Where you meet
so many people

425
00:44:53,053 --> 00:44:55,153
Who are just, like,
always so friendly,

426
00:44:55,155 --> 00:44:59,223
Always talking.
You don't even notice
anything's wrong at all.

427
00:44:59,225 --> 00:45:02,392
And then you just
hear more about--

428
00:45:02,394 --> 00:45:05,061
It's, like, one fact
about one person.

429
00:45:05,063 --> 00:45:08,130
And that is something
that I could never
even imagine.

430
00:45:13,402 --> 00:45:15,369
I don't really want
to talk about it.

431
00:47:22,189 --> 00:47:25,324
within minutes,
the failure of the peace
conference in geneva

432
00:47:25,326 --> 00:47:29,795
2,000 miles away set
off a camp-wide demonstration.

433
00:47:41,806 --> 00:47:43,873
The refugees were voicing
their disapproval

434
00:47:43,875 --> 00:47:45,941
Of the ongoing war
in syria

435
00:47:45,943 --> 00:47:48,576
And showing support
for those left behind.

436
00:47:50,846 --> 00:47:54,480
And even though these protests
will eventually disperse,

437
00:47:54,482 --> 00:47:58,317
The fighting just seven miles
away rages on.

438
00:48:16,235 --> 00:48:18,169
this is
the tip of the iceberg

439
00:48:18,171 --> 00:48:19,837
In za'atari.

440
00:48:19,839 --> 00:48:23,874
It's where you can see and
feel the conflict, actually.

441
00:48:23,876 --> 00:48:26,142
You hear the fighting.

442
00:48:29,980 --> 00:48:31,180
...Which we are not--

443
00:48:33,184 --> 00:48:35,317
at times,
our offices here have shook

444
00:48:35,319 --> 00:48:38,152
Because of the closeness
of mortar fire.

445
00:48:40,522 --> 00:48:42,923
You never get
a mental break from that.

446
00:48:42,925 --> 00:48:46,393
You're always thinking
about who's still at home.

447
00:48:46,395 --> 00:48:49,229
People are trying to
build a normal life,

448
00:48:49,231 --> 00:48:50,863
But are finding it tough.

449
00:53:13,752 --> 00:53:15,586
and what
is this again?

450
00:53:20,758 --> 00:53:22,291
And why
is he lonely?

451
00:53:37,406 --> 00:53:40,374
Is this a man who lost
all of his children?

452
00:53:40,376 --> 00:53:42,142
yes.

453
00:53:42,144 --> 00:53:43,776
Do you know anyone
who's like this,

454
00:53:43,778 --> 00:53:45,310
Who lost all of
their children?

455
00:56:02,646 --> 00:56:04,279
what do you do
at the women's center?

456
00:56:59,568 --> 00:57:00,768
So, you need
to teach us

457
00:57:00,770 --> 00:57:02,102
So we can--
so we can make--

458
00:57:05,973 --> 00:57:09,108
the center
was clearly a home
away from home for her,

459
00:57:09,110 --> 00:57:11,376
A place where
she had friends,

460
00:57:11,378 --> 00:57:13,811
Community,
access to help.

461
00:57:13,813 --> 00:57:16,980
She'd even begun
to work alongside
the jordanian staff,

462
00:57:16,982 --> 00:57:18,681
Teaching art.

463
00:58:54,040 --> 00:58:55,740
it's a very,
very important point--

464
00:58:55,742 --> 00:58:57,908
Opportunity
out of crisis.

465
00:58:57,910 --> 00:59:00,710
And that's something
we're underestimating.

466
00:59:00,712 --> 00:59:04,580
I mean, we're
focusing so much
on these responses.

467
00:59:04,582 --> 00:59:06,615
Yes, we have
to make sure that
people are warm,

468
00:59:06,617 --> 00:59:10,051
Have proper shelter,
food, water, and so on
and so forth.

469
00:59:10,053 --> 00:59:12,686
But we're forgetting
that it's really
an opportunity

470
00:59:12,688 --> 00:59:15,188
To have time
to develop and think

471
00:59:15,190 --> 00:59:16,889
And learn things.
In that sense,

472
00:59:16,891 --> 00:59:20,092
We have obligation
to invest in
the human capital

473
00:59:20,094 --> 00:59:21,960
Which this presents.

474
00:59:59,162 --> 01:00:00,762
"arr."

475
01:00:03,099 --> 01:00:04,932
No, you're
saying it, "argh."

476
01:00:04,934 --> 01:00:06,934
I can't roll my rs.
"arr."

477
01:00:21,014 --> 01:00:22,647
Sean cheats.

478
01:00:22,649 --> 01:00:23,848
Yes.

479
01:00:23,850 --> 01:00:25,316
Ha ha! What is that?

